To understand the set-theoretic definition of functions, I tried to find a set that contains a set of all functions from $A$ to $B$ for (possibly empty) sets $A$ and $B$ . $ 
ewcommand{\eqv}{\Leftrightarrow} 
ewcommand{\imply}{\Rightarrow} 
ewcommand{\powset}{\mathcal{P}} $ My approach (possibly informal): Because a function is a subset of binary relation, $$ f \in A 	o B \imply f \subseteq A 	imes B \imply f \in \powset(A 	imes B) $$ where $A 	o B$ denotes the set of all functions from $A$ to $B$ . Therefore, $$  orall f: f \in A 	o B \imply f \in \powset(A 	imes B) $$ i.e., $A 	o B \subseteq \powset(A	imes B)$ . Finally, we have $$ A 	o B \in \powset(\powset(A	imes B)) $$ Is this correct? What is the domain of discourse of $f$ here? (concerning $ orall f$ )

